No, the two lines of code you provided are not equivalent.

The first line of code:

```C#
public class customClass : base<var, var2> {}
```

This code declares a class named `customClass` that inherits from a generic base class. The base class has two type parameters (`var` and `var2`). The `customClass` class extends this base class by inheriting its functionality and may also add its own additional members.

The second line of code:

```C#
public class customClass : bas { customClass(var, var2);
```

This code is not valid and contains syntax errors. It seems like you are trying to invoke a constructor for the `customClass` class within its own definition. However, the correct syntax for invoking a constructor is not used. Additionally, the base class `bas` is not defined.

Here is the corrected code assuming you want to invoke a constructor and inherit from a base class:

```C#
public class customClass : bas
{
    public customClass(var param1, var2 param2) : base(param1, param2)
    {
        // constructor implementation
    }
}
```

In the corrected code, the `customClass` class inherits from the base class `bas`, and a constructor is defined for `customClass` with two parameters (`param1` of type `var` and `param2` of type `var2`). The `base(param1, param2)` invokes the constructor of the base class, passing the values of `param1` and `param2` to it.

No, the first line of code does not act as a constructor. It is declaring a class named `customClass` that inherits from a generic base class.

In C#, the `base<var, var2>` part in the class declaration is specifying the generic type arguments to be used for the base class. It is not equivalent to a constructor.

If you want to create a constructor for the `customClass` class using the same generic type arguments as the base class, you would need to add a constructor explicitly, like this:

```C#
public class customClass : base<var, var2>
{
    public customClass(var param1, var2 param2) : base(param1, param2)
    {
        // constructor implementation
    }
}
```

In this example, the `customClass` class has a public constructor that takes two parameters (`param1` of type `var` and `param2` of type `var2`). The `: base(param1, param2)` part calls the constructor of the base class with the corresponding arguments.

If you want to create a class similar to the `customClass` using constructor arguments instead of generic type arguments, you can define the class without using angular brackets `<var, var2>`. Instead, you can pass the required parameters directly to the constructor. Here's an example:

```C#
public class CustomClass
{
    private var param1;
    private var2 param2;

    public CustomClass(var param1, var2 param2)
    {
        this.param1 = param1;
        this.param2 = param2;

        // Other constructor logic
    }

    // Additional members and methods can be defined here
}
```

In the above code, the `CustomClass` class is defined without using generic type arguments. Instead, it has a constructor that takes two parameters (`param1` of type `var` and `param2` of type `var2`). Inside the constructor, you can perform any required logic with the passed parameters. Other members and methods can also be added to the class as per your requirement.
